<subSubSection id="A1E5F61D50073F42D5C35B061FBAEAF2" pageId="8" pageNumber="73" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="F750E0108F00C26709052C3AFA18224C" pageId="8" pageNumber="73">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="D3E64A6AA14E5F36A8C4AD24AAFA3D91" pageId="8" pageNumber="73">
At present, the only feature found to distinguish 
<taxonomicName id="4BD98BE335BCF9F4196D8EE46C770A54" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Erosne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Erosne" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Erosne</taxonomicName>
nymphs from 
<taxonomicName id="D82B0403653B7AE0D4955800CCA55396" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Amastris" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Amastris" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Amastris</taxonomicName>
is the slightly further posterior extension of the pronotum in 
<taxonomicName id="3554E8F831178FEBC86F5B9E92C6EB23" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Erosne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Erosne" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Erosne</taxonomicName>
, which is undoudtedly coupled with the more extensive pronotum in the adults. The 
<taxonomicName id="1CFF0C0AB1ACA78BC2C5B68D0428EB27" class="Insecta" family="Membracidae" genus="Erosne" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Erosne" order="Hemiptera" pageId="8" pageNumber="73" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Erosne</taxonomicName>
species examined is new.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
